            "sublevel": "expert",
            "topic": "Strings — Expert Level",
            "theory": "**String formatting styles:**\n- Old-style: `'%s is %d' % ('Alice', 30)`\n- `.format()`: `'{} is {}'.format('Alice', 30)`\n- f-strings (modern, fastest): `f'{name} is {age}'`\n\n**Raw strings** prefix with `r` — backslashes are treated literally:\n`r'C:\\Users\\file'` (no need to double the backslash)\n\n**String interning**: Python may intern commonly used strings (short, identifier-like strings) so they share the same object in memory. This is an implementation detail of CPython.\n\n**`str.encode()` / `bytes.decode()`** convert between `str` and `bytes`:\n`'hello'.encode('utf-8')` → `b'hello'`\n\n**`textwrap`, `re`, and `string` modules** provide advanced string handling including regular expressions.",
